# Supabase Auth & Data Ownership Rules

## Core Principle
ALL authentication is handled by Supabase. Users must ONLY access their own data — never another user's. Every data operation MUST be scoped to the authenticated user.

## Authentication Architecture

### Session Flow
```
Request → Middleware (updateSession) → supabase.auth.getClaims() → JWT claims → userId
```
- Sessions are JWT-based, stored in HTTP-only cookies via `@supabase/ssr`
- Middleware refreshes the session on every request
- `getClaims()` is the canonical way to get the current user — never use `getUser()` for performance

### Supabase Client Factories
- **Browser**: `src/lib/supabase/client.ts` → `createClient()` (client components only)
- **Server**: `src/lib/supabase/server.ts` → `createClient()` (RSC, server actions, route handlers)
- Never instantiate Supabase clients manually — always use these factories

## Data Ownership Enforcement

### Every query MUST filter by userId
```ts
// CORRECT — always scope to the authenticated user
const userDecks = await db.select({
  id: decks.id,
  title: decks.title,
}).from(decks).where(
  and(eq(decks.userId, userId), isNull(decks.deletedAt))
)

// WRONG — fetches all users' data
const allDecks = await db.select({ id: decks.id }).from(decks)

// WRONG — fetches by ID without verifying ownership
const deck = await db.select().from(decks).where(eq(decks.id, deckId))
```

### Ownership check on single-resource access
```ts
// CORRECT — always verify the resource belongs to the user
const [deck] = await db.select({
  id: decks.id,
  title: decks.title,
}).from(decks).where(
  and(
    eq(decks.id, deckId),
    eq(decks.userId, userId),
    isNull(decks.deletedAt),
  )
)

if (!deck) {
  throw new Error('Deck not found') // Never reveal "not yours" vs "doesn't exist"
}
```

### Child resources must verify parent ownership
```ts
// CORRECT — join to parent table to verify user owns the deck before accessing cards
const deckCards = await db.select({
  id: cards.id,
  front: cards.front,
  back: cards.back,
}).from(cards)
  .innerJoin(decks, eq(cards.deckId, decks.id))
  .where(
    and(
      eq(cards.deckId, deckId),
      eq(decks.userId, userId),
      isNull(cards.deletedAt),
    )
  )

// WRONG — no ownership check, any user can read any deck's cards
const deckCards = await db.select().from(cards).where(eq(cards.deckId, deckId))
```

### Mutations must verify ownership BEFORE modifying
```ts
// CORRECT — update only if user owns the resource
const result = await db.update(decks).set({
  title: newTitle,
  updatedAt: new Date(),
}).where(
  and(eq(decks.id, deckId), eq(decks.userId, userId))
).returning({ id: decks.id })

if (result.length === 0) {
  throw new Error('Deck not found')
}

// WRONG — updates without ownership check
await db.update(decks).set({ title: newTitle }).where(eq(decks.id, deckId))
```

## Getting the Authenticated User

### In Server Components / Server Actions
```ts
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server'
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation'

const supabase = await createClient()
const { data, error } = await supabase.auth.getClaims()

if (error || !data?.claims) {
  redirect('/auth/login')
}

const userId = data.claims.sub // This is the user's UUID
```

### In Client Components
```ts
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/client'

const supabase = createClient()
const { data: { user } } = await supabase.auth.getUser()
```

### In tRPC Context (when implemented)
```ts
// Context must resolve userId and pass it through — procedures never call Supabase directly
const userId = ctx.user.id // Set during context creation from JWT
```

## Error Handling
- Never distinguish between "not found" and "not authorized" in error messages — always return generic "not found"
- This prevents user enumeration and data leakage
- Log authorization failures server-side for monitoring

## Forbidden Practices
- Never fetch data without filtering by `userId` (or joining to a user-owned parent)
- Never trust client-supplied `userId` — always derive it from the Supabase session server-side
- Never expose another user's data in error messages or responses
- Never use the Supabase service role key in client-accessible code
- Never skip ownership checks for "admin" features unless a proper admin role system exists
- Never pass `userId` from the frontend as a query parameter — always extract from session
- Never use `supabase.auth.getSession()` for auth validation — it reads from cookies without verification; use `getClaims()` or `getUser()` instead
